{"hits": {"hits": [{"created": "2026-04-20T19:27:59.554737+00:00", "modified": "2026-04-20T19:27:59.991551+00:00", "id": 19670107, "conceptrecid": "19670106", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670107", "conceptdoi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670106", "doi_url": "https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.19670107", "metadata": {"title": "Bat pollination in a Cuban ultramafic endemic: Caesalpinia bahamensis Lam. subsp. orientensis Borhidi", "doi": "10.5281/zenodo.19670107", "publication_date": "2000", "description": "(Uploaded by Plazi for the Bat Literature Project) Pollination biology, floral characteristics, nectar secretion and breeding system of a Cuban endemic plant that grows mainly on ultramafic soils, the legume Caesalpinia bahamensis Lam. subsp. orientensis Borhidi, were studied in the ultramafic vegetation area of the National Botanical Garden in Havana, Cuba. Caesalpinia bahamensis showed floral characteristics typical of chiropterophily. The corolla, with its small inconspicuous greenish-whitish lobes, is reduced in comparison to other species of the genus. Buds opened late in the evening and each flower bloomed only for a single night. Nectar secretion was nocturnal. Mean sugar concentration of the nectar was 14% (w/w) and mean total nectar production was 205 \u242el per flower. The species is xenogamous, as selfed flowers were abscised. The natural fruiting success was low (less than 10%). The main visitor and pollinator was the glossophagine bat Monophyllus redmani Leach 1821.", "access_right": "restricted", "creators": [{"name": "Koch, Corinna U", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Guti\u00e9rrez, Jorge E", "affiliation": null}, {"name": "Rodr\u00edguez, Alicia", "affiliation": null}], "keywords": ["Biodiversity", "Mammalia", "Chiroptera", "Chordata", "Animalia", "bats", "bat"], "related_identifiers": [{"identifier": "hash://md5/172b2e4b01296e9e920161e194f1d830", "relation": "hasVersion", "scheme": "url"}, {"identifier": "hash://sha256/cce8b0e96ff3c838b76057fd745c85e4ce66a40bb98062